# Summary

Let $\inflate{r}{n}$ be positive integers. Their **least common multiple**, denoted $\text{lcm}$, is the positive
generator of the cyclic group of all common multiples of the $r_i$, that is, the cyclic group of all integers
divisible by each $r_i$ for $i = 1, 2, \ldots, n$. Note the similarity of this definition to that of the 
[greatest common divisor](greatest_common_divisor). In fact, the two are connected fundamentally by the fact that
$$ \text{lcm}(r, s) = \frac{rs}{\text{gcd}(r, s)}. $$

<div class="proof">

Let $d$ be the $\text{gcd}$ of integers $r, s$, which, by [Bezout's Identity](greatest_common_divisor#summary),
is $d = nr + ms$ for some integers $n, m$. Now $d$ obviously divides $rs$ so we can let $$ L = \frac{rs}{d}. $$
All that is left to show is that $L$ is less than all other common multiples of $r$ and $s$. Let $x$ be any common multiple;
then $$ \frac{x}{L} = \frac{xd}{rs} = \frac{x(nr + ms)}{rs} = \frac{x}{s}n + \frac{x}{r}m. $$
The right hand side of the above equation is an integer, meaning the left hand side is as well, completing the proof.

</div>

