# Direct Product Orders

Let $(\inflate{a}{n}) \in \prod_{i=1}^n G_i$. If $a_i$ is of finite order $r_i$ in $G_i$, then the order of
$(\inflate{a}{n})$ in $\prod_{i=1}^n G_i$ is equal to the least common multiple of all the $r_i$.

<div class="proof">

For a power of $(\inflate{a}{n})$ in $\prod_{i=1}^n G_i$ to give $(\inflate{e}{n})$, the power must simultaneously be
a multiple of $\inflate{r}{n}$, where each $r_i$ for $i = 1, 2, \ldots, n$ is the order of $\inflate{a}{n}$ respectively. 

</div>

